1. What is a View?
A View is a virtual table created from an existing table.

CREATE VIEW view_name AS
SELECT columns FROM table;


View does not store data;
it only stores the SELECT query logic.

  Is a View a Table?

A view LOOKS like a table,
but it is NOT a real physical table.

It is only a virtual table created from an existing table.

  Can we 'print' the student table from the view?
‚úîÔ∏è YES

    there are tow types of views
    Updatable Views vs Non-Updatable Views

Some views allow INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE.
Some do NOT allow modification.

  ‚úî UPDATABLE VIEWS

These views allow:

INSERT

UPDATE

DELETE

on the view ‚Üí which updates the original table.

üìå Conditions for an Updatable View

A view is updatable only if the SELECT query is simple:

‚úî Based on one table
‚úî No group by
‚úî No having
‚úî No distinct
‚úî No aggregate functions (SUM, AVG‚Ä¶)
‚úî No set operations (UNION, INTERSECT‚Ä¶)
‚úî No subqueries in SELECT
‚úî No joins
‚úî No expressions on columns

üéØ Example: Updatable View

Table: Employees

View:

/*CREATE VIEW emp_hr AS
SELECT emp_id, emp_name, salary
FROM Employees
WHERE department = 'HR';*/


This view is updatable.

Because it is:

From one table

Simple WHERE condition

So you can do:

/*UPDATE emp_hr
SET salary = 60000
WHERE emp_id = 1;*/


This changes the original table.
